Led Zeppelin's manager, Peter Grant, took extraordinary measures to combat live bootleg recordings at Led Zeppelin shows. He visited record stores in London and demanded all Bootleg Led Zep copies be handed over.
He monitored crowds at Led Zeppelin concerts to locate bootleg recording equipment.

At one concert at Vancouver in 1971 he saw what he thought was recording equipment on the floor of the venue and personally destroyed it , only to find out later that the equipment was a noise pollution unit being operated by city officials to test the volume of the concert.

At the Bath Festival in 1970, he threw a bucket of water over unauthorised recording equipment. 
These efforts failed to prevent the release of a torrent of Led Zeppelin bootlegs from the 1970s onwards
